1.source:
Inferno
Canto I
Nel mezzo del cammin di nostra vita
mi ritrovai per una selva oscura,
ché la diritta via era smarrita.
1.translation: Midway in the journey of our life I found myself in a dark wood, for the straight way was lost.

2.source:
Ahi quanto a dir qual era è cosa dura
esta selva selvaggia e aspra e forte
che nel pensier rinova la paura!
2.translation: Ah, how hard it is to tell what that wood was, wild, rugged, harsh; the very thought of it renews the fearl lt is so bitter that death is hardly more so.

3.translation: But, to treat of the good that I found in it, I will tell of the other things I saw there.

4.source:
Io non so ben ridir com’ i’ v’intrai,
tant’ era pien di sonno a quel punto
che la verace via abbandonai.
4.translation: I cannot rightly say how I entered it, I was so full of sleep at the moment I left the true way; but when I had reached the foot of a hill, there at the end of the valley that had pierced my heart with fear, I looked up and saw its shoulders already clad in the rays of the planet that leads men aright by every path.

5.source:
Ma poi ch’i’ fui al piè d’un colle giunto,
là dove terminava quella valle
che m’avea di paura il cor compunto,

guardai in alto e vidi le sue spalle
vestite già de’ raggi del pianeta
che mena dritto altrui per ogne calle.
5.translation: I cannot rightly say how I entered it, I was so full of sleep at the moment I left the true way; but when I had reached the foot of a hill, there at the end of the valley that had pierced my heart with fear, I looked up and saw its shoulders already clad in the rays of the planet that leads men aright by every path.

6.source:
Allor fu la paura un poco queta,
che nel lago del cor m’era durata
la notte ch’i’ passai con tanta pieta.
6.translation: Then the fear was somewhat quieted that had continued in the lake of my heart through the night I had passed so piteously.

7.source:
E come quei che con lena affannata,
uscito fuor del pelago a la riva,
si volge a l’acqua perigliosa e guata,

così l’animo mio, ch’ancor fuggiva,
si volse a retro a rimirar lo passo
che non lasciò già mai persona viva.
7.translation: And as he who with Iaboring breath has escaped from the deep to the shore turns to look back on the dangerous waters, so my mind which was stili fleeing turned back to gaze upon the pass that never left anyone alive.

8.source:
Poi ch’èi posato un poco il corpo lasso,
ripresi via per la piaggia diserta,
sì che ’l piè fermo sempre era ’l più basso.
8.translation: After I had rested my tired body a Iittle, I again took up my way across the desert strand, so that the firm foot was always the lower.

9.source:
Ed ecco, quasi al cominciar de l’erta,
una lonza leggera e presta molto,
che di pel macolato era coverta;

e non mi si partia dinanzi al volto,
anzi ’mpediva tanto il mio cammino,
ch’i’ fui per ritornar più volte vòlto.
9.translation: And behold, near the beginning of the steep, a leopard light-footed and very fleet, covered with a spotted hide!   And it did not depart from before my eyes, but did so im­ pede my way that more than once I turned round to go back.

10.source:
Temp’ era dal principio del mattino,
e ’l sol montava ’n sù con quelle stelle
ch’eran con lui quando l’amor divino

mosse di prima quelle cose belle;
sì ch’a bene sperar m’era cagione
di quella fiera a la gaetta pelle

l’ora del tempo e la dolce stagione;
ma non sì che paura non mi desse
la vista che m’apparve d’un leone.
10.translation:
lt was the beginning of the morning, and the sun was mounting with the stars that were with it when Divine Love first set those beau­ tiful things in motion, so that the hour of the day and the sweet season gave me cause for good hope of that beast with the gay skin; yet not so much that I did not feel afraid at the sight of a lion that appeared to me and seemed to be coming at me, head high and raging with hunger, so that the air seemed to tremble at it;
and a she-wolf, that in her leanness seemed laden with every craving and had already caused many to live in sorrow: she put such heaviness upon me with the fear that carne from sight of her that I lost hope of the height.

11.source:
Questi parea che contra me venisse
con la test’ alta e con rabbiosa fame,
sì che parea che l’aere ne tremesse.
11.translation: While I was ruining down to the depth there appeared before me one who seemed faint through long silence.

12.source:
Ed una lupa, che di tutte brame
sembiava carca ne la sua magrezza,
e molte genti fé già viver grame,

questa mi porse tanto di gravezza
con la paura ch’uscia di sua vista,
ch’io perdei la speranza de l’altezza.
12.translation:
And like one who is eager in winning, but, when the time comes that makes him lose, weeps and is saddened in all his thoughts, such did that peaceless beast make me, as, coming on against me, she pushed me back, little by little, to where the sun is silent.
 
While I was ruining down to the depth there appeared before me one who seemed faint through long silence.

13.source:
E qual è quei che volontieri acquista,
e giugne ’l tempo che perder lo face,
che ’n tutti suoi pensier piange e s’attrista;

tal mi fece la bestia sanza pace,
che, venendomi ’ncontro, a poco a poco
mi ripigneva là dove ’l sol tace.
13.translation: And like one who is eager in winning, but, when the time comes that makes him lose, weeps and is saddened in all his thoughts, such did that peaceless beast make me, as, coming on against me, she pushed me back, little by little, to where the sun is silent.

14.source:
Mentre ch’i’ rovinava in basso loco,
dinanzi a li occhi mi si fu offerto
chi per lungo silenzio parea fioco.
14.translation: While I was ruining down to the depth there appeared before me one who seemed faint through long silence.

15.source:
Quando vidi costui nel gran diserto,
«Miserere di me», gridai a lui,
«qual che tu sii, od ombra od omo certo!».
15.translation:
When I saw him in that vast desert, I cried to him, "Have pity on me whatever you are, shade or living mani"
"No, not a living man, though once I was," he answered me, "and my parents were Lom­ bards, both Mantuans by birth.

16.source:
Rispuosemi: «Non omo, omo già fui,
e li parenti miei furon lombardi,
mantoani per patrïa ambedui.
16.translation:
When I saw him in that vast desert, I cried to him, "Have pity on me whatever you are, shade or living mani"
"No, not a living man, though once I was," he answered me, "and my parents were Lom­ bards, both Mantuans by birth.

17.source:
Nacqui sub Iulio, ancor che fosse tardi,
e vissi a Roma sotto ’l buono Augusto
nel tempo de li dèi falsi e bugiardi.
17.translation: I was born sub Julio, although late, and I lived at Rome under the good Augustus, in the time of the false and lying gods.

18.source:
Poeta fui, e cantai di quel giusto
figliuol d’Anchise che venne di Troia,
poi che ’l superbo Ilïón fu combusto.
18.translation: I was a poet, and I sang of that just son of Anchises who carne from Troy after proud Ilium was burned.

19.source: Ma tu perché ritorni a tanta noia?
19.translation: But you, why do you return to so much woe?

20.source:
perché non sali il dilettoso monte
ch’è principio e cagion di tutta gioia?».
20.translation: Why do you not climb the delectable mountain, tP.e source and cause of every happiness?"

21.source:
«Or se’ tu quel Virgilio e quella fonte
che spandi di parlar sì largo fiume?»,
rispuos’ io lui con vergognosa fronte.
21.translation: "Are you, then, that Virgil, that fount which pours forth so broad a stream of speech?"

22.source:
«O de li altri poeti onore e lume,
vagliami ’l lungo studio e ’l grande amore
che m’ha fatto cercar lo tuo volume.
22.translation: "O glory and light of other poets, may the long study and the great love that have made me search your volume avail me!

23.source:
Tu se’ lo mio maestro e ’l mio autore,
tu se’ solo colui da cu’ io tolsi
lo bello stilo che m’ha fatto onore.
23.translation: You are my master and my author.   You alone are he from whom I took the fair style that has clone me honor.

24.translation: See the beast that has turned me back.   Help me against her, famous sage, for she makes my veins and pulses tremble."

25.source:
«A te convien tenere altro vïaggio»,
rispuose, poi che lagrimar mi vide,
«se vuo’ campar d’esto loco selvaggio;

ché questa bestia, per la qual tu gride,
non lascia altrui passar per la sua via,
ma tanto lo ’mpedisce che l’uccide;

e ha natura sì malvagia e ria,
che mai non empie la bramosa voglia,
e dopo ’l pasto ha più fame che pria.
25.translation: "lt behooves you to go by another way if you would escape from this wild place," he answered when he saw me weep, "for this beast, the cause of your complaint, lets no man pass her way, but so besets him that she slays him; and she has a nature so vicious and malign that she never sates her greedy appe­ tite and after feeding is hungrier than before.

26.source:
Molti son li animali a cui s’ammoglia,
e più saranno ancora, infin che ’l veltro
verrà, che la farà morir con doglia.
26.translation: Many are the beasts with which she mates, and there will yet be more, until the Hound shall come who will deal her a painful death.

27.source:
Questi non ciberà terra né peltro,
ma sapïenza, amore e virtute,
e sua nazion sarà tra feltro e feltro.
27.translation: He will not feed on earth or pelf, but on wis­ dom, love, and virtue, and his birth shall be between felt and felt.

28.source:
Di quella umile Italia fia salute
per cui morì la vergine Cammilla,
Eurialo e Turno e Niso di ferute.
28.translation: He shall be the salvation of that low-lying ltaly for which the virgin Camilla and Euryalus, Turnus, and N_isus died of their wounds.

29.source:
Questi la caccerà per ogne villa,
fin che l’avrà rimessa ne lo ’nferno,
là onde ’nvidia prima dipartilla.
29.translation: He shall hunt her through every town till he has thrust her back into Hell, whence envy first sent her forth.

30.source:
Ond’ io per lo tuo me’ penso e discerno
che tu mi segui, e io sarò tua guida,
e trarrotti di qui per loco etterno;

ove udirai le disperate strida,
vedrai li antichi spiriti dolenti,
ch’a la seconda morte ciascun grida;

e vederai color che son contenti
nel foco, perché speran di venire
quando che sia a le beate genti.
30.translation: Therefore I think and deem it best that you should follow me, and I will be your guide and lead _you hence through an eterna!   place, where you shall hear the despairing shrieks and see the an­ cient tormented spirits who all bewail the second death.

31.source:
A le quai poi se tu vorrai salire,
anima fia a ciò più di me degna:
con lei ti lascerò nel mio partire;

ché quello imperador che là sù regna,
perch’ i’ fu’ ribellante a la sua legge,
non vuol che ’n sua città per me si vegna.
31.translation: Then you shall see those who are content in the fìre because they hope to come among the blessed, whensoever that may be; and to these if you would then as­ cend, there shall be a soul worthier than I to guide you; with her I shall leave you at my departing.   Por the Emperor who reigns there­ above wills not that I come into His city, because I was rebellious to His law.

32.translation: In all parts is His empire, in that part is His king­ dom, there is His city and His lofty seat.   Oh, happy he whom He elects thereto!"

33.source:
E io a lui: «Poeta, io ti richeggio
per quello Dio che tu non conoscesti,
acciò ch’io fugga questo male e peggio,

che tu mi meni là dov’ or dicesti,
sì ch’io veggia la porta di san Pietro
e color cui tu fai cotanto mesti».
33.translation: And I to him, "Poet, I beseech you, by that God whom you did not know, so that I may escape this ill and worse, lead me whither you said just now, that I may see St. Peter's gate and those whom you term so woeful."

34.source: Allor si mosse, e io li tenni dietro.
34.translation: Then he set out, and I followed after him.
